   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8b7e4d5a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n",
    "    This notebook is requires installing the <tt>qiskit-ibm-runtime</tt>:\n",
    "    <ul>\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "10624c06",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background\n",
    "\n",
    "Having looked at the basics of using the `Sampler` and `Estimator` primitives in Qiskit and the Aer simulator, we are now in a position to do the same for IBM Quantum systems.  The IBM Quantum implimentation of Runtime is quite a bit more involved than that in Qiskit, as it is a full execution engine rather than a wrapper over simulators.  As such, there will be more features to learn and understand.  The goal here is to cover the majority of these options using our previous examples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "058053d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Frontmatter"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "3e392dcf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get the parameter object\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit import Parameter\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get sampled expectation value function\n",
    "from qiskit.result import sampled_expectation_value\n",
    "\n",
    "# Operators from Qiskit\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import SparsePauliOp\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get the Aer simulator\n",
    "from qiskit_aer import AerSimulator\n",
    "\n",
    "# The IBM Quantum Runtime\n",
    "from qiskit_ibm_runtime import QiskitRuntimeService\n",
    "from qiskit_ibm_runtime import Sampler, Estimator, Session, Options\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting tools\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    plt.style.use('quantum-light')\n",
    "except:\n",
    "    pass\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5ab5e085",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",

    "sim = service.get_backend('ibmq_qasm_simulator')\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,

   "metadata": {},

    "sampler = Sampler(session=sim)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "7405635d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def bv_ones_circs(N):\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(N, N-1)\n",
    "    qc.x(N-1)\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N))\n",
    "    qc.cx(range(N-1), N-1)\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N-1))\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "    qc.measure(range(N-1), range(N-1))\n",
    "    return qc\n",
    "\n",
    "N = 5\n",
    "qc = bv_ones_circs(N)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "6304259f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],

    "samp_job = sampler.run(qc)"

      ]
     },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6d5a03c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Sessions\n",
    "\n",
    "When creating our sampler object we passed the target backend `Sampler(session=backend)` in as a \"session\".  The concept of a `Session` is new, and it is a part of the IBM Quantum Runtime execution engine.  \n",
    "\n",
    "In short, a `Session` is a \"container\" that holds a collection of jobs from primitives.  In general, there are two ways this works.  First, one can have a collection of one or more jbos that are independent.  Second, one can have two or more jobs that are interconnected, with later jobs conditioned on the results from those previously executed.  This latter case is typical for iterative algorithms such as variational methods."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9b254cd6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![independent](images/runtime2/independent.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "df227d62",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "![related](images/runtime2/related.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "472ba03d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are a couple of ways that Sessions can be utilized.  First, and most ideal, as a session is connected to the backend on which it is run, we can directly create a session instance from such a backend object:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "453a2d00",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "session = Session(backend=sim)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e6fc580e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "we can then create a primitive instance using this `session`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "afee2639",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sampler = Sampler(session=session)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "26f3d11e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "or we can do what we did above and just use the backend directly:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "154dda83",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sampler = Sampler(session=sim)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c4cb8ce2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively, we can use Python contexts and have the session setup automatically within the confines of a `with`-block:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "a7a1c378",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "SamplerResult(quasi_dists=[{15: 1.0}], metadata=[{'header_metadata': {}, 'shots': 4000, 'readout_mitigation_overhead': 1.0, 'readout_mitigation_time': 0.013942512014182284}])\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "with Session(backend=sim):\n",
    "    sampler = Sampler()\n",
    "    job = sampler.run(qc)\n",
    "    print(job.result())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0fa88c22",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Everything above works for the `Estimator` as well, and we can actually mix and match within a `Session`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "f4172ac1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def cntrl_hadamard_ladder(N, measurements=False):\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(N)\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc.x(range(N))\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N))\n",
    "\n",
    "    for kk in range(N // 2, 0, -1):\n",
    "        qc.ch(kk, kk - 1)\n",
    "    for kk in range(N // 2, N - 1):\n",
    "        qc.ch(kk, kk + 1)\n",
    "    if measurements:\n",
    "        qc.measure_all()\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "411aaff5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 581.178x746.48 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 577,
       "width": 453
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "N = 12\n",
    "qc2 = cntrl_hadamard_ladder(N) \n",
    "qc2.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "2407a1cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "oper = SparsePauliOp.from_list([('Z'*N, 1)])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "dacb32ab",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with Session(backend=sim):\n",
    "    sampler = Sampler()\n",
    "    estimator = Estimator()\n",
    "    sampler_res = sampler.run(qc).result()\n",
    "    estimator_res = estimator.run(qc2, oper).result()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e34f6e11",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that in the above block we purposely waiting on the `sampler` result before sending the job for the `estimator` result.  This is because **once the code inside the context (with-statement block) is done executing, the session is closed, and the jobs no longer run back-to-back**.\n",
    "\n",
    "If instead we want to asynchrously launch several jobs within a new `Session` then we must use code like the following:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "6e3a3e70",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "session = Session(backend=sim)\n",
    "sampler = Sampler(session=session)\n",
    "estimator = Estimator(session=session)\n",
    "job1 = sampler.run(qc)\n",
    "job2 = estimator.run(qc2, oper)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f96b1996",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "where we do not call `session.close()`, at least until all of our jobs are done."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dbc98581",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setting options\n",
    "\n",
    "There are many options available to users of Runtime.  We have already changed the number of shots, but additionally, for example, we have been sending jobs to Runtime without first calling `transpile`.  Obviously there is transpilation being done by the runtime, and we should be able to modify that.  There are a couple of options to do so.  First, there is an `Options` class that allows us to set things. We can pass things in at initialization:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "97ff4139",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "options = Options(optimization_level=2, shots=1234)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a23ee3d1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "or we can use autocomplete.  For example, let us turn off Runtime transpilation altogether and change the shots"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "5f3051f3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "options = Options()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "id": "9f69f9f9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "options.transpilation.skip_transpilation = True\n",
    "options.execution.shots = 54321"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "acc3f4dd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To see a list of all the options can just look at the `Options` class:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "id": "78a13f48",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Options(optimization_level=3, resilience_level=1, max_execution_time=None, transpilation=TranspilationOptions(skip_transpilation=True, initial_layout=None, layout_method=None, routing_method=None, approximation_degree=None), resilience=ResilienceOptions(noise_amplifier='TwoQubitAmplifier', noise_factors=(1, 3, 5), extrapolator='LinearExtrapolator'), execution=ExecutionOptions(shots=54321, init_qubits=True), environment=EnvironmentOptions(log_level='WARNING', callback=None, job_tags=[]), simulator=SimulatorOptions(noise_model=None, seed_simulator=None, coupling_map=None, basis_gates=None))"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 24,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "options"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "598d1651",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can set the options for each primitive when we create it:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "id": "90bff231",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "with Session(backend=sim):\n",
    "    sampler = Sampler(options=options)\n",
    "    job1 = sampler.run(qc)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "id": "e6662907",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "54321"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 26,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "job1.result().metadata[0]['shots']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "04a55fb7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can also overload subsequent calls to primitives with a subset of options like `shots`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "id": "2c35c6c1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "session = Session(backend=sim)\n",
    "sampler = Sampler(session=session, options=options)\n",
    "job1 = sampler.run(qc)\n",
    "job2 = sampler.run(qc, shots=100)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "id": "15e08ee3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "54321\n",
      "100\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(job1.result().metadata[0]['shots'])\n",
    "print(job2.result().metadata[0]['shots'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cfbee12f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Sessions options\n",
    "\n",
    "There are a few options related to `Sessions` themselves.  Most important is the max. time of the `Session`.  For example, setting the maximum time to the 8 hour limit can be done converting the time into seconds:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "c81d8c4f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "session = Session(backend=sim, max_time=8*60*60)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b6d2cef3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Other important options deal with error suppression and mitigation.  These will be covered in the next section."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "62d0f05a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hands on example: CHSH via Runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "### Background\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"images/runtime2/people.png\"/>\n",
    "\n",
    "Alain Aspect, John Clauser and Anton Zeilinger </figcaption>\n",
    "\n",
    "This years Nobel Prize for Physics was awarded to Alain Aspect, John Clauser and Anton Zeilinger, for their pioneering work in quantum information science, and in particular their experiments with entangled photons demonstrating violation of Bells inequalities.  An experimental method by which one can test Bell's inequality was put forth by [Clauser, Horne, Shimony, and Holt (CHSH) in 1969](https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.23.880).  A few years later polarization correlations in photon pairs from Calcium atoms was observed: [Stuart J. Freedman and John F. Clauser\n",
    "Phys. Rev. Lett. 28, 938 (1972)](https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.28.938), although this experiment suffered from a number of loopholes.  These loopholes were removed in subsequent works by [Aspect et al](https://doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevLett.49.91) and [Zeilinger et al](https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.81.5039).\n",
    "\n",
    "Of particular interest is the \"locality\" loophole, where measurements of each photon in an entangled pair must be space-like separated; there is no classical signal that could be sent at the speed of light from one detector to the other to influence the detection process.  On a superconducting processor such as those from IBM Quantum, there is no way around the locality loophole any time in the near future as the distances on super conducting chips is of the order of centimeters, and the speed of light (even in metal) is tens of millions of meters per second.  However, for demonstration purposes, lets try to generate CHSH violations on IBM Quantum systems and reproduce Nobel Prize winning work."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6e58d2d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "CHSH violations are generated by looking at expectation values of measurements on two qubits prepared in a Bell state, where the basis of one qubit is varied relative to the other.  So first we need a Bell state:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "5523ca35",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 287.294x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 2,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 182,
       "width": 252
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "bell_state = QuantumCircuit(2)\n",
    "bell_state.h(0)\n",
    "bell_state.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "bell_state.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5b3ecf9e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "and second, we need create measurement circuits that measure in the bases: `ZZ`, `ZX`, `XZ` and `ZZ`.  Additionally, we will apply a parameterized `ry` to qubit 0 that varies the realtive difference between the two basis measurements (this is not strictly needed, but makes for nice plots)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 91,
   "id": "1c15ff0d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Circuit order is ZZ, ZX, XZ, XX\n",
    "theta = Parameter('$\\\\theta$')\n",
    "meas_circuits = []\n",
    "for basis in ['ZZ', 'ZX', 'XZ', 'XX']:\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(2)\n",
    "    qc.ry(theta, 0)\n",
    "    for idx, oper in enumerate(basis[::-1]):\n",
    "        if oper == 'X':\n",
    "            qc.h(idx)\n",
    "    qc.measure_all()\n",
    "    meas_circuits.append(qc)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "57da712e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "the measurement circuits are thus:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 92,
   "id": "ae0f2bb8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 496.776x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 422
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 580.387x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 490
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 496.776x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 422
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 580.387x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 490
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for circ in meas_circuits:\n",
    "    display(circ.draw('mpl'))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5c33bc91",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we need to set the values for the parameter $\\theta$ that we want to sweep over:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 156,
   "id": "669c3bbe",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Select phases from [0, 2pi]\n",
    "num_phases = 11\n",
    "phase_array = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, num_phases)\n",
    "# Format for parameter binding\n",
    "phases = [[ph] for ph in phase_array]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c0bc9877",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now lets make a collection of 4 circuits by composing the measurement circuits onto the Bell state"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 157,
   "id": "f3cf7521",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "chsh_with_meas = [bell_state.compose(circ) for circ in meas_circuits]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 158,
   "id": "441f5b94",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 747.609x284.278 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 158,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 250,
       "width": 625
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "chsh_with_meas[1].draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1984d6de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, when it comes to binding parameters in Runtime, we have some options.  Here I am going to bind the circuits ahead of time since I will demo the output without using Runtime:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 159,
   "id": "890a6a61",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bound_circs = []\n",
    "for circ in chsh_with_meas:\n",
    "    bound_circs.extend([circ.bind_parameters(ph) for ph in phases])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5c7ffbf8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are now in a position to simulate our circuits:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 160,
   "id": "b1b8b47d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "aer_sim = AerSimulator()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 161,
   "id": "ba97c7b5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "counts = aer_sim.run(bound_circs, shots=int(1e4)).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e3214beb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "collect the counts over all $\\theta$ values for each circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 162,
   "id": "069e92a6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "res = [counts[kk*num_phases:num_phases*(kk+1)] for kk in range(4)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87be1f71",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "and compute the ZZ expectation values (we applied post-rotations) for each value of $\\theta$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 163,
   "id": "3e7e7bc2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Compute ZZ expectaion values for circ ZZ at each phase angle, \n",
    "# ZX at each phase angle, etc...\n",
    "arrs = [np.array([sampled_expectation_value(cnts, 'ZZ') for cnts in item]) for item in res]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "791167c7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are two-inequalities that can be formed from the returned expectation values:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 164,
   "id": "1e8befa6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Compute CHSH for each value of theta requested\n",
    "chsh1 = arrs[0]-arrs[1]+arrs[2]+arrs[3]\n",
    "chsh2 = arrs[0]+arrs[1]-arrs[2]+arrs[3]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "185a57e8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A CHSH violation occurs when the magnitude of these CHSH values is $>2$, and is a validation of Bell's theorem; quantum mechanics cannot be desribed by local hidden variables."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 165,
   "id": "37ac5bbc",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 557,
       "width": 743
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(phase_array, chsh1, '-', label='CHSH-1')\n",
    "ax.plot(phase_array, chsh2, '-', label='CHSH-2')\n",
    "ax.axhline(2, linestyle='dashed', lw=2, zorder=2, color='0.3')\n",
    "ax.axhline(2*np.sqrt(2), linestyle='solid', lw=2, zorder=2, color='0.3')\n",
    "ax.axhline(-2, linestyle='dashed', lw=2, zorder=2, color='0.3')\n",
    "ax.axhline(-2*np.sqrt(2), linestyle='solid', lw=2, zorder=2, color='0.3')\n",
    "ax.fill_between(phase_array, 2, 2*np.sqrt(2), color='0.7', alpha=0.75, zorder=1)\n",
    "ax.fill_between(phase_array, -2, -2*np.sqrt(2), color='0.7', alpha=0.75, zorder=1)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Phase ($\\\\theta$)')\n",
    "ax.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ce8c723d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hands-on example: CHSH with Runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "The goal now is to reproduce the above using Runtime.  As it is an expectation value problem we should use the `Estimator`.  We can use the `bound_circs` from above, or we can leave the circuits unbound:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 166,
   "id": "3c8cfb83",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "unbound_circs = []\n",
    "for circ in chsh_with_meas:\n",
    "    unbound_circs.extend([circ]*num_phases)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "74d90574",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "and let the `Estimator` handle the binding for use using:\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "\n",
    "estimator.run(unbound_circs, parameter_values=phases*4,...)\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Try either of the methods on a real IBM Quantum system and see if you can get a CHSH violation.  **For testing purposes, it is best to start with the simulator first to verify your code works**"
   ]
  },
